#task 1 report
For this task, I used Canva to create an infographic on digital literacy. Canva is a user-friendly design tool that provides various templates, icons, and design elements, making it easy to create visually appealing content. My design includes key topics such as the meaning of digital literacy, useful digital tools for students, safe internet practices, professional online presence, and email etiquette. Each section is presented with short points and icons to make the information easy to understand and visually engaging.

While creating the infographic, I found it interesting to explore different layouts and color combinations to make the design attractive. One difficulty I faced was organizing the content in a limited space while keeping it clear and readable. However, using Canva templates helped me manage the layout effectively. This activity improved my creativity and design skills, and also enhanced my understanding of digital literacy concepts. It will be helpful for presentations and academic projects in the future.

#task  2 report
For this task, I created and updated my profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle. GitHub is a platform used for hosting and managing code, where developers can collaborate and showcase their projects. I created a profile README to introduce myself and highlight my learning goals. LinkedIn is a professional networking platform where I added my education details to build my professional identity. Kaggle is a platform for data science and machine learning, where users can practice with datasets and participate in competitions.

Over the next four years, I plan to actively use GitHub to upload my projects, assignments, and coding practice work. On LinkedIn, I will build a strong professional network, connect with peers and professionals, and explore internship opportunities. On Kaggle, I aim to improve my data analysis and machine learning skills by working on real-world datasets. These platforms will help me develop technical skills, build a portfolio, and prepare for future career opportunities.

#task 3 report
I used platforms like HackerRank and Google Workspace to complete this task. On HackerRank, I created an account and solved a beginner-level problem called “Solve Me First.” This helped me understand basic programming concepts and how coding platforms work. It also improved my logical thinking and problem-solving skills.

For collaboration, I used Google Forms to create a “Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz” consisting of five questions. I included both multiple-choice and short-answer questions to make the quiz interactive. I also linked the responses to Google Sheets, which helped in organizing and analyzing the data easily.

These tools are very useful for academic purposes. Coding platforms help in developing programming skills, which are important for technical subjects and future careers. Google Workspace tools improve collaboration, data collection, and presentation skills. Overall, this task enhanced my digital literacy and practical knowledge of online tools.

#task 4 report
While working on this topic, I was surprised to see how common online scams have become, especially in India. Many people lose money not because of complex hacking, but due to small mistakes like trusting unknown links or sharing OTPs. I didn’t realize earlier how risky it can be to accept random UPI requests or click on messages that look genuine.

This made me more aware of my own online habits. One thing I will definitely change is being more careful before clicking on any link or making online payments. I will always check the details properly and avoid trusting unknown sources. This topic helped me understand that staying safe online is mostly about being alert and thinking before acting.

